the east end and the third bay from the west end on the fa\'E7ade, each featuring non-historic metal and glass doors flanked by single-light sidelights and topped with an oversized three-part transom.\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 The bay directly west of the east entrance on the fa\'E7ade contains\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 an overhead garage door that allows access to a loading dock.\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\li360\ri711\qj\sl240\slmult1\sb275\f0\fs24\b0\expnd0\expndtw0\charscalex100 A limestone sill course separates the ground floor from the upper section of the fa\'E7ade, which features a regular grid of window openings separated by vertical brick piers and brick spandrel panels. The upper sections of the piers are ornamented with simple Prairie-style brick horizontal and vertical elements, and a corbeled brick frieze runs between the piers above the fourth story. The fa\'E7ade is topped with a dentil frieze and simple metal cornice. Windows on the second story of the fa\'E7ade are wood double-hung windows grouped in pairs at the east and west end bays and threes at the center bays. Windows on the upper two stories are non-historic aluminum double-hung windows.\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 A metal balcony has been attached at a window opening near the center of the fa\'E7ade at the third story; this window opening features a center metal and glass door that\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 provides access to the balcony.\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\sl240\slmult1\f0\fs24\b0\i0\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\li359\ri710\qj\sl240\slmult1\f0\fs24\b0\expnd0\expndtw0\charscalex100 The west and south elevations of the building are common brick and are regularly fenestrated with a combination of wood and non-historic aluminum windows set within segmental arch openings.\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 Some window openings on the first story of the west elevation have been altered or bricked in, and several openings on the upper stories have been enlarged and fitted with doors that provide access to the exterior metal fire escape.\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 A ground-floor entrance at the south end of the west elevation provides access to basement-level parking.\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\sl240\slmult1\f0\fs24\b0\i0\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\li359\sl240\slmult1\f2\fs24\b0\i1\expnd0\expndtw-2\charscalex100 Interior\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\li359\ri715\qj\sl240\slmult1\f0\fs24\b0\expnd0\expndtw0\charscalex100 The interior of the S. Birkenstein & Sons Company Building originally contained offices on its first floor, and open storage and sorting space on its upper floors. The building was converted into rental offices sometime in the 1980s or 1990s,\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 but retains many of its industrial features, including exposed wood posts, beams, and ceiling structure and exposed brick exterior walls.\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\sl240\slmult1\f0\fs24\b0\i0\par\pard\plain\s1\nooverflow\nocwrap\lnbrkrule\li360\ri713\qj\sl240\slmult1\f0\fs24\b0\expnd0\expndtw0\charscalex100 The east and west entrances on the fa\'E7ade lead to small vestibules equipped with non-historic staircases and lifts that provide access to the raised first floor.\expnd16\expndtw80  \expnd0\expndtw0 The floor is partitioned into offices and retail spaces that are located on either side of a U-shaped corridor that connects the east and west entrance vestibules.\expnd8\expndtw40  \expnd0\expndtw0 A set of double-leaf doors on the west wall of the lobby leads to the main staircase, which was rebuilt in a new location during the office conversion. An elevator\expnd0\expndtw-1  \expnd0\expndtw0 is located near the\expnd0\expndtw-1  \expnd0\expndtw0 center of the south\expnd0\expndtw-1  \expnd0\expndtw0 section of the corridor;\expnd0\expndtw-1  \expnd0\expndtw0 an\expnd0\expndtw-1  \expnd0